note: Extremely faint CME with uneven front seen to the East in C2 and COR2A. Source is very uncertain, but one candidate is an area of very subtle dimming seen at 2023-10-02T16:54Z in SDO AIA & GOES SUVI 195 spanning from about N05E22 to N05E00(AR 13453) down to S10E00. Centered at about S05E10. This dimming is possibly associated with a C-class flare and small eruption from AR 13450 (S10E07) seen starting at 2023-10-02T15:54Z. Alternatively, the CME could be backsided but we were not able to identify any backsided coronal signatures for it. This CME overlaps with a previous slow outflow CME seen also to the East with a source more likely beyond the limb, further complicating analysis.

note: Bright loop seen to the NW in all coronagraphs that becomes faint decently into C3 and COR2A. The source appears to be over the West limb, likely old AR 3444 which would be around N22W100 at this timestamp. The only notable source signature is moving field lines in SDO AIA 171/193, first seen wiggling around 2023-10-03T08:12Z and opening more rapidly around 2023-10-03T09:09Z. This is pretty close to when the CME is first observed in coronagraphs however, so the field lines may be extending well out of SDO's view.

note: High latitude 3-part CME with flux rope visible in coronagraph. However this source does not produce a fit in swpc_cat, so the source is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME in the NW with the source likely a very minor filament eruption behind/on the NW limb starting 2023-10-04T08:30Z seen in AIA 171/304. We should note that there is also a faint minor dimming on disk around that time close to(N20W70), however this is a less likely source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME is first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is a small piece of ejecta seen just beyond the NW limb 2023-10-05T01:04Z in SDO AIA 304 and opening field lines on the NW limb in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Beautiful prominence eruption seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. Source is a prominence that was hanging well above the solar surface, almost out of SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304's view before erupting. The prominence is best seen in GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 304, resting close to the NE limb throughout 2023-10-03 -> 2023-10-04 and beginning to separate and rise further around 2023-10-04T18:04Z. It slowly rises higher in altitude until about 2023-10-05T01:16Z, when it finally splits apart into an eruption, also observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as some field line movement around the same time. As the prominence rose so high before eruption, pinpointing a surface lat/lon is almost impossible. We do know it took place on or near the NE limb at a high latitude before deflecting a little southward as the material expanded within SOHO LASCO C2's FOV.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint CME in the NE which overlaps with the outflow of a previous CME. The field lines are faint but the movement spans from an apparent latitude of N25 to N60 when looking at UV imagery.

note: High latitude filament eruption seen to the NNW in all coronagraphs. Source is a filament that appears to have spanned around the west limb before erupting, from approximately N55W55 -> N60 and over the limb at 2023-10-12T10:00Z. This filament began to lift around 2023-10-12T10:00Z, whipping eastward as it erupted around 2023-10-1216:29Z with a large portion of the filament material falling back down to the sun, interestingly, fairly close to the meridian. This large spread of longitudes the filament is witnessed over as it erupted made it difficult to determine a source longitude, but the latitude range is quite high regardless, between N55-N70. The filament is best seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, but also observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as filament material and slight brightening on the disk underneath the eruption.

note:
Likely filament eruption seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source is likely a piece of a larger filament that was responsible for CME 2023-11-19T21:24Z, as we observe the east-most part of that filament lag behind, deflect eastward, and erupt a bit later in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 around 2023-11-20T21:39Z. SDO AIA 171/193 also observe this motion well in the field line movement. 

Source is a filament over the high NE limb, first seen erupting over the limb at 2023-11-19T20:49Z in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Additionally observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as moving field lines at the same time. As the filament source is far-sided, we do not observe the source longitude, but it is estimated to span around E120-E160 at a high latitude prior to erupting. During the eruption, a piece of the filament lags behind and may be responsible for a separate CME: 2023-11-20T00:12Z shortly after.

Source is an on-disk filament near the SE limb, spanning approximately S25E55 to over the SE limb around S45 at 2023-12-09T07:51Z before erupting, best observed in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304. This filament rises and twists for a while, losing a lot of material back to the surface (can be seen hitting near the limb) and "fizzling" out in GOES SUVI 304's wider FOV. This CME is difficult to track in coronagraphs, likely due to the nature of this eruption. Also observed as some dimming centered around S28E52 in SDO AIA 193 and field line movement in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The eruption is seen as a mid-size dimming area in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. This source is a bit early and did not line up well in triangulation with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A measurements however, so the source remains unclear.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The potential source is a filament eruption starting around 2023-12-15T20:48Z in SDO AIA 304 that is also visible as dimming in SDO AIA and brightening loops in SDO AIA 94 around 2023-12-15T21:05Z. note: A CME in the SW with uneven/dimpled front. Its source is likely the C8.3 class flare from AR 3514 (N06W76) peaking at 2023-12-16T13:58Z and the associated minor eruption with opening of field lines seen in AIA 171/193 starting 2023-12-16T13:30Z.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The potential source eruption is more clearly seen on the west limb from the point of view of STEREO A, with opening field lines and brightening visible along post eruptive arcades. This eruption may be associated with an active region that has recently rotated off of the Earth facing disk, such as AR 3514, which is around latitude N05 and rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2023-12-17.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible in the west of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and partially overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2023-12-18T10:36Z. There are several potential sources: One is opening field lines beyond the limb in SDO AIA 171/193 starting around 2023-12-18T12:27Z, but the eruption is unclear, and this may be field line movement that continues following the eruption triggering CME: 2023-12-18T10:36Z. Another candidate source is visible on the disk in EUV imagery around S10W35. A faint EUv wave can be seen in SDO AIA 193 starting around 2023-12-18T09:34Z and brightening can be seen on the disk in SDO AIA 94 around 2023-12-18T09:45Z. A third candidate can be seen around N10W70 in STEREO A EUV 195 with dimming seen from 2023-12-18T11:35Z-13:35Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraph imagery. Moving/opening field lines can be seen in SDO AIA 193 imagery starting around 09:40Z, with dimming visible to the north of the eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Overlaps a slow streamer blowout which also appears to be sourced from behind the SE limb, which measured at 188 km/s before being overtaken by this event. The source for this CME may be on or just beyond the SE limb evidenced by field line movement in SDO AIA 171 in the vicinity of AR 3540 and other potential active regions yet to rotate onto the disk around 2024-01-04T16:00Z/T16:48Z.

note: Very faint narrow CME in the West best seen in SOHO LASCO C2. Its front is super diffuse in C3. Its front is too faint to be seen in STEREO A COR2 and is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. Source is likely the opening of some field lines from behind the SE limb starting around 2024-01-13T12:40Z in SDO AIA 171 and STEREO EUVI A 195 after 15Z, indicating a source potentially behind the limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the S/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraph imagery. The source is likely a far-sided filament eruption which begins to lift-off around 2024-01-15T23:00Z from beyond the SW limb as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 304 imagery. Field line movement is visible around this time in SDO AIA 171 as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery but is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely far-sided with possible field line movement visible beyond the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery around 2024-01-16T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint diffuse CME in a series of fronts to the northeast, with the start partially covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2.  This CME is likely the widest in the consecutive fronts. The source of this CME was not found on the Earth-facing disk and is likely behind the limb. This front is closely followed by a 2024-01-17T01:26Z faint front, very similar to this front, which merges with it.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint CME in a series of CMEs/outflows closely following each other. Its source is possibly close behind NE limb, indicated by low post-eruptive arcades at lat ~24 in AIA 193 starting 2024-01-17T03:27Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint front ENE in a series of faint ENE CMEs closely following each other. No clear source found but there is minor flaring on/close to the NE limb, e.g. there is a C1.7 class flare close to the limb (~N27E87) peaking at 2024-01-17T05:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Slow lightbulb CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. Source of this CME is field line movement and slow liftoff of material seen beyond the northern limb in SDO AIA 171 lasting from about 2024-01-19T06:00Z to 2024-01-19T16:30Z. Movement of material can also be seen on the northern limb in SDO AIA 304 around 2024-01-19T13:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Semi-faint CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a far sided filament eruption starting around 2024-01-20T19:36Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. The filament has a "shredded" appearance to it, possibly creating multiple fronts within one feature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. Not visible in STEREO A imagery due to data gap. This CME is quickly overtaken by the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-01-21T00:36Z. There is no clear source for this CME, but it appears to have a potential faint shock ahead of a main "bulk" portion. Both features are very faint and difficult to see in white-light imagery (easier to see in motion in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME with no well-defined leading edge visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No source is seen on the disk in available EUV imagery, but rapid field line movement/restructuring of field lines can be seen on the west limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-01-22T14:03Z, and the CME likely originates on the far side. This partially overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-01-22T10:48Z. A faint shock may potentially be associated with this CME, as seen in about 3 frames of early SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, but it fades quickly from view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME with no well-defined leading edge visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This partially overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-01-22T10:48Z. A faint shock may potentially be associated with this CME, as seen in about 3 frames of early SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, but it fades quickly from view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the NW. A potential front-sided source is an eruption of a filament centered around N40W11 as seen in AIA 304/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the NW. A potential front-sided source is an eruption of a filament centered around N40W11 as seen in AIA 304/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible in the SW of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. STEREO A COR2 has a data gap starting at 2024-01-24T15:38Z. The flare and brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 131/193, opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171/193, and dimming is visible in SDO AIA 193. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195 imagery.

note: A narrow faint CME in the SW, the beginning of which is covered by a data gap in STEREO A. Alternatively, there is also a slow movement/opening of field lines behind the SW limb starting after 19Z indicating a possible backsided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME in the SW. Its source could be the short duration C5.7 class flare from AR 3561 (S17W54) peaking at 2024-01-24T21:40Z. Alternatively, there is also a minor slow movement/opening of field lines in the SW after 2024-01-24T21Z.

note: Faint and narrow CME with just a couple timestamps that it is seen in SOHO LASCO C3 bc of faintness. One possible but rather unlikely source is a small filament eruption centered around (S15E60) starting at 2024-01-26TZ as seen in AIA 194/304. Deflection south should be very significant for this source though since the CME is directed towards the south. There is a much more minor eruption (barely noticeable) located around (S50E50) at the same time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Visible in north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is on the far side. The eruption can be seen beyond the limb in GOES SUVI 304 around 2024-01-27T03:49Z. This CME overlaps with CME: 2024-01-27T03:36Z in the field of view, but this eruption appears to be separate from the eruption that triggered the earlier CME, based on timing and direction.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible in the far north of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No source location is visible in available EUV imagery, and the CME is likely backsided. The leading edge is unclear, and fades away in later SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 frames.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A in COR2 in real-time due to a data gap. The leading edge of the CME fades away quickly in SOHO LASCO C3 by around 2024-01-27T18:18Z. The source is on the far side. Opening field lines can be seen in SDO AIA 171/103 around 2024-01-27T14:55Z. Material can also be seen ejected beyond the east limb in GOES SUVI 304. A candidate region for the source of this eruption is seen around longitude E150 in NSO GONG imagery on 2024-01-27.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to an eruption visible beyond the NE limb in SDO AIA 304 imagery starting around 2024-01-27T16:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

Opening field lines can be observed at this time near the western limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Visible in the NE of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The candidate source eruption can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-01-29T06:41Z. Rising/moving field lines are also seen in GOES SUVI 171 and 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is related to an eruption just on or slightly beyond the western limb starting around 2024-01-29T09:15Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with fuzzy front, with potential source flare and eruption from near the SE limb, at around S20W80 seen ~15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east in coronagraphs that overtakes a previous even fainter and much slower eastern CME. No clear source was found in EUV imagery. There is a very minor loop from behind the E limb seen in SUVI 171 around 2022-02-12T01:36Z but it seems too minor. Alternatively, there is a relatively faint but large in area dimming near the coronal hole in the east starting around 2024-02-11T23:45Z and centered very approximately around S01E20, however frontsided longitude does not produce a fit in swpc_cat.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME to the NW seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is overtaken by a much larger CME. Source is dimming and opening field lines associated with the M6.5 flare. Opening field lines with heavy northern deflection along with dimming and some ejecta seen at 2024-02-12T03:55Z in SDO AIA 171/193/304, centered at S10W20 near AR 3576, AR 3578, and AR 3579. Associated with an M6.5 flare from AR 3576.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The start time is approximate due to the faintness in SOHO LASCO C3. Following the event, post-eruptive arcades are visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source candidate for this CME. There is a small eruption around N20E25 starting around 2024-02-14T07:20Z in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304, but this eruption appears to be deflected more northward. There may also be faint field line movement seen beyond the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, suggesting a far sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely on the far side, as no clear candidate is on the Earth-facing disk. Opening field lines can be seen on the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-02-14T10:51Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Diffuse CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a set of successive opening field lines on the SW limb, with the identified leading edge at 2024-02-15T01:36Z likely attributable to the instance of opening field lines seen occurring at 2024-02-15T00:52Z in SDO AIA 171. A subsequent instance of opening field lines are seen from the same location starting at 2024-02-15T02:33Z as seen in SDO AIA 193, which likely resulted in an additional faint front first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-02-15T03:24Z. There is an earlier instance of opening field lines at 2024-02-14T22:42Z in SDO AIA 193 with related dimming seen centered at W70N10 at 2024-02-15T00:36Z, but this does not seem to have resulted in any visible CME.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Visible in the east of SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-02-24T14:53Z to 2024-02-25T03:09Z. Source is a small filament eruption seen centered at S12E75 in SDO AIA 304 at 2024-02-24T16:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint puff-like CME feature to the NE seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 during this event. There is no clear source for this CME and the front is fairly faint/diffuse which limits trackability into the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. Source appears to be far-sided, evidenced by field line movement over the NE  in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-02-2702:51Z. A weak eruption from AR 3595 on-disk starting around 2024-02-27T04:06Z lines up closely, but appears to be ruled out as a candidate as the field line movement is observed first.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the S in all coronagraphs. Reanalysis of this CME from the initial entry finds the source to be front-sided, sourced at a filament centered around S38E02 (spanning approximatley S48W14 to S32E10) at 2024-02-27T08:01Z when it began to lift off best seen in SDO AIA 304. The filament fades moreso than it is observed leaving the disk, but it is the best candidate source and aligned well with coronagraph analysis between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Source of this bright lightbulb-shaped CME in the NE is possibly a medium-size dimming near the NE limb (~N35E50) starting around 2024-02-28T08:30Z. However, there is also an more complex faint sigmoid filament eruption in the NE quadrant seen in AIA 304 as post-eruptive arcade and in AIA 193 as arcades and a relatively faint dimming. The erupting filament seems to stretch from from AR 3594 northeastward to AR 3596 and might be centered around (N20E35) but its center is hard to determine because of the complexity and dimness of the coronal signatures.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The leading edge first appears in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-02-29T09:28Z, but an additional faint, potentially separate front is first visible in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-02-29T09:48Z. This is not clearly distinguishable as a separate, measurable CME. A potential source is seen near the western portion of AR 3590 (approx. N20W70), with eruption best seen with dimming and moving field lines around 2024-02-29T08:25Z from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195. The eruption is also best seen in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the N in all coronagraphs. Source is very likely far-sided, as no on-disk EUV signature is observed. However, no EUV signature is observed at all of this event between SDO and GOES, so a far-sided fit was made using triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery to determine the source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the S in all coronagraphs. Source is very likely far-sided, as no on-disk EUV signature is observed. However, no EUV signature is observed at all of this event between SDO and GOES, so a far-sided fit was made using triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery to determine the source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the S in all coronagraphs. Source is likely far-sided field line movement over the southern limb beginning around 2024-03-03T10:15Z, best seen in SDO AIA 171. This CME is overlapped by other slightly earlier far-sided CMEs but has a separate, fairly distinct source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME appears as continuous outflow visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely far-sided with field line movement visible beyond the NE limb starting around 2024-03-04T21:20Z seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery.

note: Faint and narrow jet-like CME to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2. The source may be a brief eruption from AR 13595 with associated filament ejecta/jet seen starting around 2024-03-06T00:00Z in SDO/AIA 304.

note: Faint outflow looking CME to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. note: Faint CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and very faintly in C3, not in STEREO COR2A due to a lengthy data gap and faintness when imagery returns. A large western portion of the filament appears to deflect south/southeast, which is likely associated with this event. Dimming is visible from the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 shortly after the filament lifts-off and field line movement can be seen near the S/SW limb at this time in SDO AIA 171. Post-eruptive loops begin to form around 04:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery. This event partially overlaps CME: 2024-03-17T03:12Z, which also likely occurs from the same filament eruption.

The material is heavily deflected to the south/southeast. Other signatures include liftoff of prominence material seen in SDO AIA 304, opening field lines and loop of material seen in SDO AIA 193. The eruption appears to deflect towards the southwest, and an EUV wave is visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery around 20:00Z which also extends south and southwest. Additionally, field line movement is visible over the southern limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 19:45Z.

The source is a filament eruption starting at 2024-04-17T20:04Z from AR 3638, best observed in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 as outflowing dark material, deflecting southeastward as it travels. This eruption is paired with very a impulsive double peaked C9.0 and C9.7 flare best seen in SDO AIA 131. Slight dimming and field line movement observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint partial halo CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source is likely a massive dimming region (spanning approximately E35->E15 and S10->N12) following some weak field line and loop breaking (observed across wavelengths SDO AIA 131/171/193/211) from AR 3645, which begins around 2024-04-17T22:09Z and dims until about 2024-04-18T02:09Z. A slow rise in x-ray flux is noted in SDO AIA 131 and GOES real-time x-ray flux over this time but no "flare" occurs. This dimming notably begins well before the start time giving some lower confidence, but this region gave an excellent visual fit in SWPC_CAT during the measurement process compared to other longitudes or Plane-Of-Sky.

note: Faint filament eruption to the SE seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and a few frames of C3. This eruption is paired with an M2.2-Class flare best seen in SDO AIA 131, which peaked at 2024-04-18T02:48Z. Slight dimming and field line movement observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as well. A wider front to the north of this one emerging at 2024-04-18T04:12Z is likely from this same eruption, measuring 230 km/s as a Plane-Of-Sky.

note: Loop CME seen to the SW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain, and possibly the strangest signature I've witnessed in SOHO. At 2024-04-26T13:25Z in SOHO LASCO C2's FOV, an area of empty space in the SW portion of the image seemingly "splits" apart, with one loop falling back to the disk and the other projecting out as the analyzed front. Since the front is not visible emerging from the disk and rather as described, that first visible timestamp is used as the start time. It is difficult to trace back to the disk for a source region, potentially observed as some field line movement off the SW limb around 2024-04-26T13:01Z in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284.

note: [TRUE START TIME 2024-05-04T00:00Z IN LASCO C2 - RETAINING COR2A/T01:53Z START TIME DUE TO DELAY]. CME seen to the NE in STEREO COR2A and later in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 after a delayed backfill. STEREO had also just left a data gap, spanning 2024-05-03T11:23Z to 2024-05-04T01:53Z, which is marked as the first visible frame for this CME. The source is not clear in EUV imagery outside of SDO AIA 131 (detailed below). The best sources for this are two of three flares from AR 3663 (around ~N26W03 at this time). These flares, best observed in SDO AIA 131, are an M1.0 and M2.4 peaking at 2024-05-03T23:16Z and 2024-05-03T23:30Z respectively. Additionally, a third flare from AR 3663 occurring just after the CME is visible in SOHO, an M1.6 peaking at 2024-05-04T00:36Z, launched a small front visible ~2024-05-04T02:12Z in SOHO LASCO C2 for 3-4 frames before likely colliding into this CME--so all three of these flares were measured as one.

The feature appears to have a narrow portion related to the ejecta that separated from the more rounded filament eruption which may have contributed to a fainter wider front that disappears before exiting the C2 field of view. There are associated moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but there are two possible candidates, both seen starting at about 2024-07-06T17:00Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193: opening field lines on or just beyond the W limb, centered at about N05 or some field line movement/possible small field line opening/possible small post-eruptive arcades seen from ARs 3729 and 3733 (S05W50 and N05W50, respectively).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME and streamer blowout visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. An exact source is unclear, but there is continuous slow field line movement in the NE quadrant of the disk close to the NE limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Another messy loop CME seen to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is field line movement seen on the W limb in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-07-06T12:16Z. Possibly some very subtle opening field lines and a possible post-eruptive arcade with footpoints at N05W70 and S05W70 seen in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-07-06T11:21Z (opening field lines) and 2024-07-06T14:10Z (arcade). Data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery from 2024-07-06T13:38Z to 2024-07-06T15:38Z affected analysis of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME in the west mostly seen in SOHO coronagraphs (only one, poor quality, image is available from STEREO A because of a large data gap). No clear source have been found. There is a preceding eruption from Active Region 13740 (S18W26) starting around 2024-07-08T14:45Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery, however the analysis with this longitude does not produce a good fit when using the single available STEREO image.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note:
A relatively bright complex-shaped CME with two lobes seen in the west in coronagraphs. The source is likely a clear opening of field lines seen in SUVI 284 on or behind the west limb after 2024-07-08T21:30Z. STIX instrument on the SolarOrbiter registered an equivalent of an M1.1 flare from the west limb (for Solar Orbiter) at 2024-07-08T21:21Z, confirming the possible source of this CME as behind the west limb (for SOHO and STEREO A). 
An alternative source could be an eruption between Active Regions 3739 and 3734 centered (~S02W50) which is first seen around 2024-07-08T21:20Z in AIA 304 and (as minor dimming) in AIA 193, however the fit of this CME with two coronagraphs gives higher longitudes than 50 degrees (between 90 and 110 degrees).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint and narrow CME to the southwest seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2, seen for only a few early frames in C3 because of its faintness. The source is very uncertain, as there are several small movements of field lines and small areas of brightening occurring across the disk at the time, however, the strongest candidate is a very small eruption from Active Region 13740 (S18W52) seen as very narrowly opening field lines around 2024-07-10T08:15Z in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME in the northeast in coronagraphs where the source is a filament eruption beyond the northeast limb clearly seen in AIA 171/193/304 lifting off after 2024-07-11T01:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Well-defined leading edge with cavity containing material following. Source is a streamer blowout seen as opening field lines and possible slow-moving ejecta originating from about N10W90 in SDO AIA 131/171/193 at about 2024-07-11T21:12Z-23:58Z. Small eruption with ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting at 2024-07-11T14:13Z, but it slows down significantly before leaving the FOV and is possibly the triggering eruption for this streamer blowout. A broader opening of field lines can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting later at 2024-07-11T20:01Z. Small eruption with ejecta is also seen in SDO AIA 171/193, but possible relationship to streamer blowout is most clearly seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

More evidence for this source comes from a broad post-eruptive arcade over the region forming around 2024-08-02T02:24Z.

note: Faint, wispy CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. This CME also triangulated well to W90 during measurement, further corroborating a source on/very near the limb.

note: Faint but distinct loop CME seen to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The time at which this CME first enters the C2 field of view is probably a bit earlier than 06:48Z, but the leading edge is not clearly discernable in C2 imagery (both white light and difference imagery) in any frames before 06:48Z when it is about halfway through the C2 field of view. The exact source location is uncertain due to the faintness of the event, but the strongest candidate source is a set of loops of field lines seen in the SE quadrant of the disk, which showed movement (and possible ejection of some material) starting around 2024-08-03T03:30Z. These loops of field lines in the SE span from E40 to E80, and their footpoints appear to be anywhere from S10-S25 and are tilted south.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Best observed in SDO AIA 304 as the filament material ejecting, but also seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as field line movement, in SDO AIA 304 as brightening on the surface, and a post-eruptive arcade forming around 2024-08-07T02:12Z across all wavelengths.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption seen on the northeast limb at about N17E90 in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284. Field line movement and a small bright loop can be seen as early as 2024-08-07T00:38Z in GOES SUVI 284 and 2024-08-07T00:58Z in SDO AIA 193. The small loop of field lines that brighten is located at an apparent latitude of N17 and is on or very close to the East limb. There are faint opening field lines surrounding this loop seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at roughly 2024-08-07T01:03Z and extending from apparent latitudes of about S05 to N20 on the E limb. The exact location of source may possibly extend beyond the E limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME first seen by SOHO LASCO C2 in the NW beginning at 2024-08-07T03:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. Possible source is a C8.5 flare from N05W85 peaking at 2024-08-07T02:01Z as seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an M5.0 flare peaking at 2024-08-07T18:54Z from AR 3777. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-08-07T17:23Z to 23:09Z. Dimming, opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 193, and the eruption appears to be directed towards the southeast. A possible faint, separate halo component may also be seen in early frames of SOHO LASCO C2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint halo CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C3 beginning at approximately 2024-08-08T05:30Z. This event is too faint to confidently track in SOHO LASCO C2 or STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is an M1.3 class flare from AR 3777 (S05W15) peaking at 2024-08-08T04:41Z as seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Halo CME first seen by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-08T20:00Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The beginning of this event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-08-08T19:38Z to  2024-08-08T22:53Z. The source of this CME is an X1.3 class flare from AR 3777 (S05W25) that peaked at 2024-08-08T19:36Z. This flare can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with an EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. Resulting field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-09T01:25Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is an eruption of a filament on the NE limb that lifts off at approximately 23:09Z from approximately N40E60 as seen in SDO AIA 304. Field line opening can also be seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The first portion of this filament erupts at approximately 22:43Z and resulting in an earlier CME, CME: 2024-08-08T23:24Z which measured below 250 km/s.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME with the front best seen in SOHO LASCO C2 but also traceable in a couple of early timestamps in C3. The CME front is not seen in STEREO A (although imagery is available).  No source for the CME was found on disk but there is a tiny post-eruptive arcade seen from behind the west limb in AIA195/131 starting around 2024-08-09T05Z, possibly indicating a source behind the west limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely faint CME, barely seen in white light imagery and better seen in difference imagery. No clear source has been found on the Earth-facing disk, however an extremely faint dimming, followed by equally faint post-eruptive arcades is seen in AIA 193/211 centered roughly around (N30E35) starting with 2024-08-09T07Z. There is also a faint movement of field lines behind/on the eastern limb but the fit with two coronagraphs does not fit the close to the limb source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a clear front only in a few early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, with fuzzy front in C3 and STEREO A COR2. The clear source is an opening of field lines in SDO AIA 171 beyond NW limb starting at 2024-08-09T23:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the NE in STEREO A COR2. It later overlaps in the field of view with CMEs 2024-08-10T03:12Z and 2024-08-10T03:24Z. The CME could not be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, possibly due to the overlapping features of the later CMEs. The source could not be found, and it may be backsided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, slow CME seen to the far north in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is on the far-side of the sun, at an apparent high latitude. Observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and well in GOES SUVI 284 as field lines first opening over the NNE limb around 2024-08-10T22:31Z, and a secondary, wider field line opening starting around 2024-08-11T00:51Z. This eruption is wide and slow, and evolves into a dimpled front in the furthest coronagraph imagery from its the initial frames as the filamentary material is uniquely observed unfurling in coronagraphs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow loop CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and possibly extremely faintly in STEREO A COR2. There is no discernable distinct source. This CME overlaps and overtakes a much slower CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-08-10T21:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This narrow CME is seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and faintly in STEREO A COR2. The source is a small filament eruption on or just beyond SE limb accompanied by opening field lines, as seen in SDO AIA 304/171/193 starting at about 2024-08-11T09:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint narrow jet visible in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO/LASCO coronagraphs, with the front mostly seen in the running difference imagery.  No clear source for this CME has been found on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, jet-like CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. There are no clear source signatures seen on this disk for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T08:24Z, as well as in later frames by STEREO A COR2. This event was too faint to be seen clearly in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is a small eruption from the vicinity of AR 3785 (S18E45). Material is seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA 304 and minor post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-13T00:12Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this eruption is a thin release of material from approximately S30W90+ that exhibits strong Southeastern deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor jet CME seen to the south in C2, C3, and COR2A, especially in running difference imagery. May be associated with a very minor eruption at far southern latitudes on the Earth-facing disk seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 04:03Z near S70W40.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-13T06:24Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a long, thin eruption off of the SW limb (approx. S30W90+) exhibiting strong Southeastern deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines can also be clearly seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east, clearer seen in STEREO A coronagraph imagery. It has two lobes moving in unison. The source of this event seems to be indicated by the opening of field lines on/near the east limb, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171 imagery after 2024-08-13T09Z, and by a small area of post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284 close to (S04E70) at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet CME seen to the south in SOHO C2/C3 imagery. The source is not clear as there is no evidence of moving field lines off the southern limb in available GOES/SDO imagers, so potentially the source is located on the far side of the Sun.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fairly narrow CME seen to the north at very high northern latitudes associated with a filament eruption that is seen best in SDO 171/304 after 2024-08-13T18:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Complex CME seen to the southwest made up of several disjoint fronts that all seemingly move together, the leading edge begins to become more diffuse in later frames. Associated with rapidly opening and breaking magnetic field lines near the vicinity of AR3777 (S10W86).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a narrow ejection of material from a small region near S08W70. This small eruption begins at approximately 2024-08-14T02:30Z and appears to exhibit some deflection to the NW as seen in SDO AIA 304. This CME overlaps with CME: 2024-08-14T04:12Z in later frames preventing analysis further into the field of view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Third in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Exact source is uncertain, but is likely associated with the continuous field line movement seen on the west limb in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. Not visible in COR2 due to a data gap in STEREO A lasting from 2024-08-15T17:53Z to 2024-08-15T22:23Z and due to the faintness of this event. Source is a small eruption seen from beyond the N/NE limb starting at 2024-08-15T18:03Z in SDO AIA 304, at an apparent latitude of N60. Small amount of ejecta seen in SDO AIA 171 starting at 18:18Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-16T02:00Z as well as in later frames by SOHO LASCO C3. This event is too faint to be reliably tracked in STEREO A COR2. There is not distinct source seen for this event however small eruptive activity is seen in the vicinity of AR 3790 (S14E70) at this time as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and NE in STEREO COR2A. The source is an eruption from AR 3789 starting around 2024-08-16T13:52Z as field line movement and ejecting material in SDO AIA 171/193/211/304, alongside a C5.9 class flare which peaked at 2024-08-16T14:09Z best seen in SDO AIA 131. Eruption on the north end of the AR. Light dimming also observed reverberating across a broad area NE of the region in SDO AIA 193/211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR 2 imagery for a few frames prior to a data gap starting at 2024-08-16T17:53Z. The source is likely related to a small eruption near Active Region 13780 (S10E85) starting around 2024-08-16T15:20Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a small eruption near the western limb starting around 2024-08-17T06:20Z seen best in SDO AIA 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely an M1.6 flare and eruption from Active Region 13784 (N17W41) starting around 2024-08-17T10:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Faint dimming is visible northwest of the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 shortly after the flare is observed.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames among a data gap in STEREO A COR2 data. The frames in STEREO A COR2 are fairly noisy during this event. The source of this CME could potentially be a filament eruption visible along the N/NW limb believed to be on the far-side of the sun as seen in SDO/AIA 304. There are a few fronts visible in the coronagraphs that appear associated with this eruption, this front is first seen starting around 16:00Z while an earlier much slower front is seen starting around 15:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The leading edge becomes diffuse towards the end of the COR2A field of view. There is no clear source for this CME on the disk in UV imagery and therefore is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs, but weakly in SOHO LASCO C3 as it fades. The source for this CME is uncertain, as the only observed source of field line movement starts around 2024-08-20T00:12Z in SDO AIA 193 over the NW limb, at the same time the CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2, making it unlikely.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is brightly visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is not clear, but may be associated with faintly visible slow moving field lines along the SE limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-19T23:00Z. There is a dimming visible on the disk to the NE of AR 13790 starting around 2024-08-20T00:40Z, however the directionality of the dimming does not correlate well with the directionality of the CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east where a possible source could be a minor dimming on or near the east limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint jet to the southeast, fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A imagery. No source has been found on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and very faint field line movement is visible beyond the western limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-08-21T02:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: A faint CME to the E seen in both coronagraphs with the likely source being a minor on-limb filament eruption in the New (unnumbered) AR on the SE limb (S10E77) seen in AIA 304 at 04:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-22T10:00Z. The source of this event is a C5.6 flare from AR 3801 (N09E71) peaking at 2024-08-22T08:08Z seen in SDO AIA 131. Field line opening is also seen in GOES SUVI 284
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint partial halo CME visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of the CME may be a filament and possible flare starting around 2024-08-23T01:00Z from AR13794 (N20W30) based on SDO/AIA 131 and 304. Dimming is also visible to the SW of the eruption location - best seen in SDO/AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no corresponding source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no corresponding source signatures on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and for 2 brief frames to the S in STEREO COR2A as it was in a lengthy data gap over this CME duration. The source for this CME is uncertain, but thanks to the two frames in STEREO COR2A a triangulation was made around S42W24 via swpc_cat, with some speculation due to the single-frame triangulation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, though very faint in C2 to the point of being unable to distinctively define its start time around the occulting disk, so T17:24Z was used as the best reference for visibility in C2. No source observed for this CME in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to be far-sided, observed best as field line movement on the east limb starting around 2024-08-24T20:18Z in SDO AIA 171, likely deflecting northward observing its travel path from SOHO LASCO C2 to C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME tracking/overlapping with outflows following the 2024-08-24T21:12Z CME and similarly consisting of two lobes moving at the same pace. No on-disk source was found for this CME in the EUV imagery, so it is likely farsided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T12:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. A majority of this CME is obscured by data gaps (SOHO: 28/14:36Z to 29/04:35Z, COR2A: 28/14:23Z to 28/23:09Z), so analysis of this event is based solely on later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is dimming seen around N45W40 as seen in SDO AIA 211 beginning at approximately 28/11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-08-28T18:15Z. There is no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery available for this event due to a data gap from 28/14:36Z to 29/04:35Z. The source of this CME is clear opening field lines seen along the SE limb by SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284, likely representing a far sided source. However the CME itself is fairly faint.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely a super minor eruption off/behind the northeast limb seen after 2024-08-29T18:45Z in AIA 304 and as minor moving/opening of field lines in AIA 193. The CME is covered in STEREO A COR2 by a data gap and is seen very faintly in C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME in the northeast where the source could be a minor filament eruption centered around N22E47 and spanning from N12E30 to N39E50. The filament is seen in SDO AIA 304 lifting off at 2024-08-29T23:21Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source is likely a filament eruption just NE of AR 13804, beginning around 2024-08-30T22:48Z and centered around N20E28. Observed as filament material ejecting and brightening in SDO AIA 304, and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source is far-sided, observed best as field line movement over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-08-31T00:12Z, with initial more southern movement seen starting around 2024-08-30T23:42Z which likely resulted in CME 2024-08-31T01:38Z. This CME's parameters are difficult to pin down, due to an ongoing campaign with SOHO impacting available LASCO C2/C3 imagery for triangulation with STEREO COR2A.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME with kinked front seen to the northwest and eventually southwest in later frames in SOHO, seen to the northeast in STEREO Ahead. May be associated with changes in the northward side of AR3807 with a minor eruption around 02:15Z (S16W19). The spot region then becomes stable after this, from 03Z onward.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T16:24Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. there is not STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap beginning at 03/14:38Z. The source of this CME is wide opening field lines seen off of the West limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning at approx. 03/15:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is no available STEREO A COR2 data for this event due to a data gap from 2024-09-03T14:38Z to 2024-09-03T22:53Z. A potential source is opening field lines seen in SDO AIA 171/193 starting at 2024-09-03T17:02Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-04T15:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME appears teardrop shaped in coronagraph imagery, but a faint leading edge is visible. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some minor field line opening can be seen off of the West limb in SDO AIA 193 beginning at approximately 04/14:30Z. There is limited STEREO A data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap that began at 04/16:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME northeast in SOHO and northwest in STEREO A COR2, with no source found.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME to the south, with coronal signatures that include a wide opening of field lines/departure of mass from the corona best seen in EUVI A 195, high rising post-eruptive arcades and dimming to the west and south of AR 3815 in AIA 193 after the associated flare, as well as a movement of a loop/ejecta and a wide opening of field lines seen in AIA 171 to the south.  In AIA 304 a sigmoid filament structure lights up but it is not clear how much of it departs the corona. The CME displays multiple different consecutive fronts - at the very least it has two lobes (possibly two simultaneous CMEs) - the southern brighter lobe and the more eastern faint one better seen in COR2A (but too faint to see in C3).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, faint, jet-like CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C/C2 and STEREO A COR2. The source eruption can be seen from an active region near the limb from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195, best characterized as opening field lines starting at 2024-09-07T10:35Z. It is also visible as opening field lines beyond the west limb in SDO AIA 171/193/335.

note: Wide CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is near the west limb in SDO AIA imagery, with an material seen lifting off in GOES SUVI 304 around 2024-09-07T20:16Z. The source eruption was not visible in STEREO A EUV due to a data gap from 2024-09-07T19:35Z-22:35Z. The start of the CME is obscured by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-09-07T20:23Z-22:38Z.

Dimming is seen in SDO AIA 193 around N40E30, which appears to be an EUV wave propagating from the source of the partial halo eruption, and a dark feature can be seen at the same location in SDO AIA 171, possibly indicating northeastern-directed ejecta at about 2024-09-08T01:17Z, also located at roughly N40E30. This CME is more defined in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 than in STEREO A COR2.

note: Lightbulb-shaped CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a long and narrow horizontal area of very gradual dimming and gradual field line movement seen centered at N50 and stretching from E20 to W70 in SDO AIA 193 / 171. It is difficult to pin down an exact start time for the field line movement at this area on the disk, but best estimate is 2024-09-19T04:54Z as seen in SDO AIA 193, with dimming becoming more clear by 07:50Z. Subtle field line movement can be seen on the NW limb starting as early as 2024-09-19T05:48Z in SDO AIA 171/193. GOES SUVI instruments were in an eclipse at and around these timestamps.

The main source is a brightening between ARs 3860/3859 centered around S05W61, observed in SDO AIA 131 alongside field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193 and some surface brightening in SDO AIA 304, beginning around 2024-10-22T17:04Z. No clear source is seen on disk in EUV imagery.

Flickering magnetic field lines are observed off the northeast limb nearly simultaneously after the on-disk signature seen in SDO AIA 171 which may suggest, with low confidence, a possible simultaneous far-side component. Triangulation of the CME using SOHO/STEREO A coronagraphs suggested with higher confidence that the CME was predominantly associated with the on-disk signatures.

S20E05 as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 and 211

note: CME first visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-18T03:24Z. Also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME erupted very slowly at first with speeds around 63 km/s, accelerating to a more constant speed by ~2024-11-20T23:00Z well into LASCO C3's FOV. The source is far northern latitude field line movement on or beyond the NW limb, observed best in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2024-11-19T08:00Z and accelerating faster around 2024-11-19T12:30Z.

One possibility is some brightening and activity just to the NW of AR 3905 best seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 00:08Z. This coronal signature is likely too late to be the source. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 at this time as well.

There are some faint moving field lines off the SW limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2024-12-02T17:00Z that continue for a few hours that could be associated with this CME.

The CME becomes appear bright in initial imagery and well-defined and becomes more diffuse with time, eventually losing its leading edge.

note: CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only, missed in STEREO COR2A due to a data gap spanning this event. The source for this CME appears to be far-sided, and may be continued outflow following the larger, fast CME 2024-12-05T15:48Z which was analyzed far-sided to S47E124. Field line movement over the SSE limb in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-05T16:30Z may correlate to this event, but this movement may just be continued from 2024-12-05T15:48Z as well.

Source is subtle and slow field line movement from on or beyond the SW limb, seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as 2024-12-06T13:00Z with a slightly more distinct outflow of material seen at about 14:10Z. Opening field lines on the SW limb can also be seen in GOES SUVI 195 at 14:20Z.

note: This CME is faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like/outflow-like CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a very small faint eruption near N20E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-07T03:50Z.

note: Faint front overlapping with the 2024-12-07T04:12Z CME. No clear source was found for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, although there is minor activity from the Active Region 13913 and north of it going on all morning.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like/outflow-like CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a very small faint eruption near N20E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-07T06:50Z. (Follows very similar path to the CME first seen at 2024-12-07T04:24Z).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint narrow CME in the southwest following the 2024-12-07T04:12Z CME.

note: Initially bright but very messy front to the SW in COR2A and C2. note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a small eruption from Active Region 13916 (S16E13) starting around 2024-12-08T04:10Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery which appears to deflect towards the southeast.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk which agree with the measured longitude of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a faint and minor eruption centered near S50E40 as seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery around 2024-12-09T23:10Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery and at least one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is unclear but could be a small eruption from AR 13920.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event. The source appears to be far-sided with moving/opening field lines visible along the S/SE limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-10T15:42Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively slow and wide CME seen to the south in SOHO LASCO imagery and southeast in STEREO A COR2. Very similar in appearance to the far-sided 2024-12-11T12:12Z CME, there are a few sources on the Earth-facing disk including an eruption on the western portion of the disk, but triangulation strongly suggests this event is far-sided. No candidate sources for this CME were observed in EUV imagery. The CME is quite difficult to measure in LASCO C2 with the CME off the southeast (CME: 2024-12-11T06:24Z) obscuring the CME in question (more evidence this is far-sided).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and north in STEREO A COR2 with faster/protruding leading edge/nose feature. Likely associated with far-sided activity as few, if any, sources were observed in GOES SUVI on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively slow and minor CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, seemingly associated with point-source eruption from AR 3916 (S14W46) with some southward deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Not seen well in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and the south/southwest in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a C2.1 flare starting at 2024-12-13T02:21Z from old Active Region 3916 (currently a plage), around S15W55. The eruption is best seen with brightening and an ejecta of material in GOES SUVI 304. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304. The CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-13T11:38Z. The source is not clearly visible in available EUV imagery, and the CME may originate from the far side.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Thin minor jet only seen in SOHO LASCO imagery but not in STEREO A COR2. No source for this CME has been found on the disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint northern CME with the source an eruption starting around 2024-12-14T09:20Z in the NW quadrant centered ~(N34W60), as seen in SUVI 195/304/284, with narrow ejecta in 304 to the N and dimming/minor post eruptive arcades in 195/284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, 3-part CME visible to the S/SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery starting around 2024-12-15T01:25Z. The source of this CME is a long filament stretched from W10 to W60 along the S25 latitude that erupts starting around 2024-12-14T21:50Z with full lift off by 2024-12-14T23:50Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible along the SW in GOES SUVI 284. Sympathetic eruption appears to occur around/within AR 13924 which is visible as brightening in GOES SUVI 195. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades are visible in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME overlapping a bright streamer to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a C-class flare and associated filament ejecta from decayed AR 13916 (S15W85) visible in GOES SUVI 304, 284, 131, and STEREO A EUVI 304 starting around 2024-12-15T09:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet-like CME first seen in the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3. A majority of this event is obscured by a data gap in STEREO A COR2A lasting from from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this CME as it is likely far sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:24Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is limited COR2A imagery for this event due to a data gap from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. There is not a clear source candidate for this CME. Field line movement was visible on the west limb in GOES SUVI 195, but no clear source on the disk could be found. This CME may originate on/beyond the west limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very narrow jet CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery but not observed in STEREO A COR2. Possibly associated with a minor eruption located near the vicinity of AR 3926 (S20E55), but the source of the eruption is unclear, as the EUV signature doesn't show a definite jet signature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption starting at 2024-12-17T03:52Z in GOES SUVI 304 around S10E80. Opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 171/195/284. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption that appears to have a footpoint located at approximately S40E40 and a footpoint that wraps beyond the east limb as seen in available GOES SUVI imagery. Filament liftoff is seen starting at 2024-12-17T06:40Z in GOES SUVI 304. Dimming and opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 195 and opening field lines are seen in GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the east in SOHO LACSO C2/C3, not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-17T11:36Z. The source is not clearly visible, and it may be farsided. Field line movement may be seen near the limb in GOES SUVI 171/195/284 from approximately 2024-12-17T07:00Z to 13:00Z, but no clear eruption is seen and no source location can be determined.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T10:00Z. Also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3. The majority of this CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. The source of this CME is most likely some moving field lines on or just behind the E limb beginning around 2024-12-18T07:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T11:12Z. Also visible to the NW for a couple frames in SOHO LASCO C3 but is very faint. CME is mostly covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. The source of this CME is most likely some minor brightening and general, continuous activity best seen in GOES SUVI 304 from AR 3920 in the NW for a few hours prior to and after the CME first emerges into SOHO LASCO C2, but there is no clearly definitive source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T12:48Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. A possible source of this CME is some very minor activity to the north of AR 3924 at approximately S06W70 best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2024-12-18T10:31Z. It is also possible that the source of this CME is far-sided as there is not a definitive source candidate on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T18:24Z. Also visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no definitive source candidate on the Earth-facing disk, so this CME is likely far-sided. A far-sided source is consistent with measurements.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint "puffy" CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME is not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-12-18T18:53Z to 2024-12-19T01:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-19T03:48Z that is easier to see in running difference imagery. This CME does not make it beyond the field-of-view of SOHO LASCO C2 and is not visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely a small amount of activity and brightening starting about 2024-12-19T01:45Z best seen in GOES SUVI 304 on the W limb at about N10. This is just to the SW of AR 3920 which was at about N22W83 at the time of eruption.

note: CME with trianglular/trapezoidal shaped leading edge seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO and farther to the west in STEREO A; was initially theorized to be associated with front-sided filament eruptions on the Earth facing disk in the southwest limb around 2024-12-19T22:00Z, however, triangulation suggests that this eruption is far-sided. Possibly associated with a far-sided eruption corresponding starting around 01:00Z that erupts distinctly different than the filament eruption seen in GOES 304 seen best in GOES 93/171/284 composite imagery off the southern limb and propagating to the southwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME to the southwest with a possible source a very minor movement/opening of field lines behind the southwest limb around 2024-12-20T21:30Z.

note: Narrow faint CME to the E. A minor eruption off the southeast limb seen in SUVI 195 around 2024-12-20T21:05Z with movement/opening of field lines seen in SUVI 284 starting 21:15Z was explored as a source, however the fit with two coronagraphs doesn't support the longitude close to -90 deg.

instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, directly following CME: 2024-12-21T21:12Z in the field of view of the coronagraphs. The potential source is near or beyond the west limb as seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUV imagery. In GOES SUVI 304, ejecta can be seen departing on the limb starting at 2024-12-20T23:00Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 195/284 and STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely on the far side, and rapidly opening field lines are visible beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 195/284 starting at 2024-12-21T09:20Z. Field line movement is also faintly visible in STEREO A EUV 195 imagery. The CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-21T11:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no clear source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-22T21:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-12-23T11:09Z to 2024-12-23T01:09Z and limited STEREO A data due to an ongoing campaign. The source of this CME is an M1.1 flare from AR 3932 (S16E37) as seen in GOES SUVI 131. Field line opening is also visible in GOES SUVI 195 and 284, along with a region of dimming to the SW of the region in GOES SUVI 195, suggesting a Southwestern deflection.
