note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and in two frames of STEREO COR2A following a data gap resuming at 2024-12-23T01:09Z. The source for this CME is uncertain and not observed in available GOES SUVI imagery, indicating a likely far-sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, but is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk that clearly align with this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and related to an opening of field lines visible slightly beyond the western limb in GOES SUVI 171 and 284 imagery starting around 2024-12-23T06:00Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 with faint shock/leading edge seen farther to due east, likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by a prominence eruption seen best in GOES SUVI 304 behind the southeast limb around 2024-12-24T04:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, "puff"-like CME first seen to the WSW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-24T08:24Z. Also seen to the WSW in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is best seen in running difference imagery. STEREO A is in campaign mode during this event with limited to no imagery. There is no good source candidate for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, so the source is most likely far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively wide, bright CME in SOHO LASCO running difference imagery seen to the southeast and much fainter in white light imagery, likely associated with an M4.1-flare from AR13932 (S17E17) with an associated eruption. In addition to the flare seen in GOES 131 imagery, a significant looking eruption in GOES 284 with a large magnetic loop and dimming signature around 2024-12-24T08:30Z is observed near the vicinity of the active region.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Slowly developing loop seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery during a STEREO A data gap. Characterized by a dimming (GOES SUVI 284) and destabilization near AR 13934 (N15E02) with northeastward deflection, a surge in GOES SUVI 304, and change in magnetic field structure with rising structure in GOES SUVI 195/171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-25T21:12Z. The actual start time will be a bit earlier; the CME is first visible in white light imagery after a short gap in SOHO LASCO data from 2024-12-25T20:36Z to 2024-12-25T21:12Z. CME is also visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3. The CME maybe be visible for one or two frames in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap from 2024-12-25T13:38Z to 2024-12-25T21:53Z. The source of this CME is most likely ejecta from beyond the SE limb. The ejected material is best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting about 2024-12-25T20:48Z. Some field lines opening beyond the SE limb are best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting abut 2024-12-25T20:07Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-26T15:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 26/15:23Z. The source of this event is an eruption seen beginning at approx. 26/13:48Z located at approx. S05E85 as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Subsequent field line opening is also visible in GOES SUVI 185 and 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow faint outflow to the SSE - one in a group of three narrow CMEs. The source could be a narrow ejecta in SUVI 304 at 21Z and opening/movement of field lines behind the SE limb seen in SUVI 284 around 20:59Z, although this source could be behind two other closely following CMEs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with the front only clearly seen in COR2A. The start is likely much earlier but it is covered in COR2A by a STEREO data gap. No clear source of it has been found, although there is constant minor activity in AR 3938 in the morning.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very narrow and faint outflow/jet preceded by a super faint wider front. The source might be minor flaring and narrow ejecta from AR 3938 (N19E22) seen in SUVI 304 ~2024-12-28T05:28Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk which fit this event between coronagraphs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint very slowly developing partial halo CME to the southwest, with filamentary structures seen in coronagraph and with multiple consecutive fronts. There is activity on/close to the SW limb early in the morning (opening/movement of field lines close to the limb and some dimming/brightening), but it is happening after 01:30Z and so is unlikely to be the source of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-12-30T10:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2 in later frames. This CME fades before exiting the field-of-view in SOHO LASCO C2 and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this event is an eruption seen near AR 3939 (S17E15) with post-eruptive arcades and dimming  seen in SUVI 195/284 after 08:30Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-31T00:12Z. Also visible to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME might be very faintly visible STEREO A COR2 for two frames, but it is not definitively this CME. A possible source candidate is some minor brightening and activity from AR 3936 starting about 21:48Z visible in all GOES SUVI wavelengths, but measurement does not closely match this source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME with a fuzzy front (multiple fronts) to the SW. A possible considered source could be a significant eruption near AR 3939 (S17W15) starting around 2025-01-01T00:30Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery. An alternative source is the movement of field lines close to/on the SW limb seen in SUVI 195 after 2025-01-01T01:30Z, possibly from Active Region 3932 (S15W77).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the SSW, not seen in STEREO A because of a data gap from 2025-01-01T04:38Z to 2025-01-02T01:23Z. No clear source found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME to the NW in SOHO, fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. Two potential sources are activity from from AR 3936 starting about 2025-01-01T10:36Z, a minor filament eruption from AR 3934 on the NW limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-02T03:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line movement tracing down to an unnumbered region located at approximately N20E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-02T03:36Z, as well as by STEREO A COR2 in later frames before a data gap begins at 2025-01-02T04:38Z. N15E47 in SDO AIA 193, 211 and 304.

There is a concurrent, separate M1.8 flare from AR 13990 (S12E13) which peaked at 2025-02-14T20:57Z which was considered for a source here, but ruled out with lower confidence than the SE quadrant dimming mentioned prior.

A well defined loop with filament ejecta in the middle is seen lifting from the source region with clear moving/opening field lines and EUV wave to the south starting around 2025-03-01T23:00Z. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 14/15:53Z. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 4022 (N08E11) beginning at approx. 14/14:28Z. Dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 suggest a strong Eastern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely narrow faint jet seen mostly in running difference imagery in SOHO and STEREO A to the northeast. No clear source has been found in the EUV imagery at the time but there is a super minor ejecta in SDO AIA 304 at 01:40Z on the NE limb which may be related.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet/outflow seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and in 2 timestamps surrounding a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint and narrow CME best seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a couple of early timestamps of C3 and fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely faint fuzzy CME/outflow/possible partial halo to the north-northwest, seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and even more faintly for a few early timestamps in C3, but not seen in STEREO A COR2, likely because of faintness. Better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is most likely the medium-size but pretty faint dimming seen starting ~2025-03-16T10:09Z, signifying eruption to the northwest of Active Region 4023 and centered (~N20W10), seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME with bulk seen to the north-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more towards the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery with faint, very wide shock developing in later frames with invisible leading edge containing lobes to the north and east in both SOHO and STEREO A imagery. The presumed source is an eruption from near the vicinity of Active Region 4032 (N35E35) seen as a dimming in SDO AIA 193 as early as 2025-03-16T18:04Z, disappearing loop structure in SDO AIA 171, and brightening in SDO AIA 304. There are two eruptions seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery emanating from the same area, one seen at 18:49Z and another which appears more Earth-directed at 20:49Z. Triangulation using SOHO and STEREO A imagery seems to more strongly support Earth-directedness and deflection westward than the EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very slow CME that looks like a slow streamer blowout, with a succession of almost identical faint fronts seen in both coronagraphs. The CME seems to accelerate, as seen in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. There is no clear source seen on the disk, although there is a super minor dimming in AIA 193 centered around N30E10 starting after 00:30Z and continuing until 05Z, but it is extremely faint.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2. Also seen to the S in STEREO A COR2 but is not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. A possible source candidate is a very small eruption far to the SE (~S60E10) best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2025-03-17T08:07Z; measurements align well with this possible source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-03-17T11:36Z. Also seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C3 but not visible in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). The source of this CME is likely a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow pointy-nosed CME/outflow to the north, following preceding CMEs. No clear source has been found for it on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T19:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in a second overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T20:12Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T03:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.0 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright streamer blowout CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is visibly wider in STEREO A COR2 imagery than in SOHO imagery. The source of this CME appears to be a complex series of eruptions beginning with an eruption near N05E05 starting around 2025-03-19T00:39Z. This eruption may have triggered additional instability of nearby magnetic field line foot points, which may be associated with the streamer itself. Dimming is clearly seen to the east of the initial eruption location starting around 2025-03-19T06:00Z. It is also around this time that the CME appears to begin to speed up in the SOHO field of view with a more clear/defined front appearing around this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. This CME is slow to evolve and appear as a defined front in the LASCO C2 field-of-view, and appears more clear in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source for this CME is not observed as a distinct source, but appears to be continued outflow from CME 2025-03-20T17:12Z from AR 14022 centered at N08W75, corroborated via triangulation in the STEREO_CAT tool.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME may be the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) as seen in SDO/AIA 131 and 193. There is clear dimming and moving/opening field lines visible to the SW of the eruption suggesting deflection. This may be due to a coronal hole due north of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption near Active Region 14037 (N22W32) starting around 2025-03-22T13:20Z seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, constant outflow of minor fronts to the northeast from approximately 2025-03-23T08:36Z to 2025-03-23T13:25Z, with two of the fronts being more prominent: this one is the earlier of the two, and becomes more discernible in SOHO C3 white light and running difference imagery with time. The two more prominent fronts seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's field-of-view around 13Z. No clear source has been found for these outflows.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the West in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-25T10:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is too faint to be reliably tracked in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a C4.4 class flare from AR 14028 (S16W86) which peaked at 2025-03-25T09:49Z. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with field line opening visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a C9.5 flare from AR 14028 (S16W86) seen peaking at 2025-03-25T12:29Z. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with wide field line opening and slight dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

This CME is also not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 25/16:09Z to 26/03:23Z. N20E70) beginning at approx. 26/13:28Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171 and 195.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-21T10:12Z. Also visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C3 and for a few frames in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely an eruption near the WNW limb starting around 2025-04-21T08:45Z. It is seen across all SDO AIA wavelengths; however, it is best seen as some brightening and field line movement on the WNW limb in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source of this CME is most likely some plasma seen leaving the disk off the WNW limb, best seen in SDO AIA 193 and SDI AIA 171 starting around 2025-04-21T12:43Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet CME seen to the west-northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs, potentially associated with an eruption beyond the western limb as seen by moving field lines in SDO AIA 171 off the northwest limb around 2025-04-22T15:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, puff-like loop CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the northwest and widening with time as the CME propagates, the CME is with high confidence likely originating from the far-side as suggested by this geometry and there are no sources on the Earth-facing disk to suggest this CME originates from the Earth-facing solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2. Source is suspected to be a gradual streamer blowout, and there is some dimming visible in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-04-23T06:40Z from N20W45, which may be indicative of a footpoint of one of the rising loops of this streamer liftoff.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SW in STEREO A COR2 imagery. No SOHO imagery available currently due to a data gap. The source appears to be beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-04-23T07:53Z in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 171 as moving/opening field lines. The source is not clear in STEREO A EUV imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-27T17:00Z. CME is also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not visible in STEREO A COR2. The CME is visible in running difference imagery one frame earlier than in white light imagery. The source of this CME is most likely a small filament eruption from on/near the E limb starting around 2025-04-27T16:14Z as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME to the NE in SOHO, best seen in running difference imagery. It has a fuzzy front (except in a couple earliest timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2). The CME is extremely faint in C3 and even in C2 the front disappears after a few early timestamps. The CME is fully covered by a nighttime data gap in STEREO A. Its source is most likely an eruption best seen in GOES SUVI 284 from an unnumbered AR/plage region (~N20E40) to the NE of AR 14076 beginning at 2025-04-27T23:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the south southeast in STEREO A COR2, with a clear flux rope seen in C2 running difference imagery. The source could be a minor eruption just west of AR 4068, centered ~(S25W20) at 2025-04-28T07:19Z seen in SDO AIA 304/193, on the boundary with the eastern part of the large SW coronal hole (so there could be an eastward deflection).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-28T15:48Z. Also seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is best seen in running difference imagery and partially overlaps with earlier, slower CME: 2025-04-28T10:36Z. Later in propagation into SOHO LASCO C3, the CME appears to accelerate. This acceleration could be caused by an additional front that is sporadically visible for a few frames across SOHO LASCO C2/C3 but is not independently measurable. No additional coronal signatures were visible as possible sources for this CME; however, due to the far northern latitude (~N85), a very wide range of longitudes are possible. The source could be farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Second of three of a series of minor visible outflows seen to the north and northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 occurring between 2025-04-28T23:00Z and 2025-04-29T03:24Z; probably far-sided as suggested by the continued appearance of similar-looking outflows despite no major source signature on the Earth-facing disk; some weakly moving field lines high off the northern limb between 2025-04-29T02:00Z and 04:00Z may suggest far-sidedness of at least one of these events. This event is seen in STEREO A COR2 due to the northwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Third of three of a series of minor visible outflows seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 occurring between 2025-04-28T23:00Z and 2025-04-29T03:24Z; probably far-sided as suggested by the continued appearance of similar-looking outflows despite no major source signature on the Earth-facing disk; some weakly moving field lines high off the northern limb between 2025-04-29T02:00Z and 04:00Z may suggest far-sidedness of at least one of these events. This event is seen in STEREO A COR2 due to the northwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like, narrow CME with diffuse leading edge seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and also to the west in STEREO A COR2; the source is not clear but may be potentially associated with an eruption occurring near or just beyond the western limb as seen in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO AIA 171 around 2025-04-29T07:00Z.

note: Faint, jet-like CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-19T13:24Z. This CME fades before exiting the FOV in C2, and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is minor brightening and field line movement seen near AR 4079 (N09E75) exhibiting Northern deflection in SDO AIA 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the West by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-04-29T17:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, as triangulation suggests a far sided source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint narrow CME with a peculiar slanted front seen to the east in both coronagraphs. No clear source for it was found in EUV imagery, although there is continuous minor movement of field lines beyond the east limb seen in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint CME seen to the east in both coronagraphs (but only seen very faintly in a couple early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C3). No clear coronal signatures for this CME were found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-05-03T11:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 beginning at approximately 2025-05-03T10:39Z centered at approximately N10E55, but exhibiting some Eastern deflection. Dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 211 and post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 131 and 193.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint and narrow CME visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source appears to be a small eruption located to the NE of AR 14071 near N20E55 starting around 2025-05-04T03:10Z in SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This CME is visible for a few frames before becoming too diffuse to track. The source appears to be a small filament eruption from AR 14081 as seen in SDO/AIA 304, 193, and 171 starting around 2025-05-04T07:04Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the west in SOHO C2, SOHO C3, STEREO A COR2A, and GOES CCOR-1 similar in appearance to the 2025-05-04T15:23Z CME which has no clear source on the Earth facing disk in any EUV imagers, indicating that the source is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity relative to the Earth-facing solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Slow, wide CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 / GOES CCOR1, visible in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap from 2025-05-04T21:38Z to 2025-05-05T01:53Z. Associated with an eruption occurring behind the western limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 284 imagery seen around 2025-05-05T00:08Z with strong opening field lines after 01:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright loop front CME with outflowing material following it to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is a filament eruption in the NE starting around 2025-05-07T11:00Z in SDO/AIA 304, 171, 131, and 193. The filament appears to stretch over the NE limb, possibly by 20 degrees based on a rough STEREO A EUVI 304 calculation. There is limited imagery available in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap for most of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Third of three CMEs seen to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and not seen in STEREO A COR2A white light but perhaps in one frame in running difference imagery; a possible source is a minor eruption or series of eruptions in Active Region 14079 (N08W46) with broad moving field lines seen best in SDO AIA 171 between 2025-05-08T07:00Z and 12:00Z and some brightening post-eruptive arcades, especially in the northern extent of Active Region 4079.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like CME, less than a half-width of 10 degrees, to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and not observed in STEREO COR2A or GOES CCOR-1. The source may be a small filament ejecta on or around the NE limb around N10, observed in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2025-05-09T06:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME seen to the southwest in SOHO C2, GOES CCOR1, and STEREO A COR2 associated with a very minor filament eruption occurring near S30W65 near 2025-05-09T08:30Z best seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. A very faint partial-loop (which is the brightest in a series of similar loop-like CMEs (2025-05-09T21:36Z, 23:36, 2025-05-10T01:25, 02:00Z, 03:12, 06:36, 09:48Z). These loops are likely associated eruptive activity AR 4079. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 or GOES-CCOR1. It is possible that 21:48Z loop might be associated with the C1 flare from AR 4079 (N05W64) peaking at 20:21Z or with a very minor filament eruption seen in AIA 304 at 21:09Z (both very minor events).

note: Very faint high southern latitude CME (or a series of very faint consecutive fronts) that looks like a follow-up for 2025-05-09T21:12Z CME, seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. The front is too faint to be traceable in STEREO A COR2 except for a couple early timestamps. The source of this CME is likely a southern filament eruption close to the SW limb extending from around (S40W75) southward and showing mostly as dimming close to the SW limb see in AIA 193 at 2025-05-10T08:42Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A high northern latitude CME from near the northeast limb seen in SOHO LASCO and STEREO A, covered by pylon in GOES CCOR-1, and likely associated with the filament eruption/bright ejecta close to the northeast limb (~N40E75) and seemingly directed/deflecting northwardly in EUV imagery, as seen starting in SDO AIA 171/304 and GOES SUVI 304 EUV imagery starting after 2025-05-11T02Z. It is also seen as opening of field lines in GOES SUVI 284 and as minor post-eruptive arcades in SDO AIA 193.

note: A faint CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 and northeast in STEREO A COR2 in the early time stamps only, with front not clearly seen in C3 at all. The source could be a northern eruption seen as a very faint dimming in SDO AIA 193 at ~N30W05 (east of a small coronal hole) at 2025-05-11T05:40Z.

note: A super faint loop CME seen mostly in the running difference imagery to the south-southwest in both coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). The start of this CME is likely hours earlier. Its front is not seen in C2 and appears in COR2A and C3 after 2025-05-12T04Z, when it is halfway through the field of view.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint halo seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and in C3 in the early timestamps, and later seen as almost a full halo in C2, but not seen at all in the STEREO A coronagraph even though imagery is available, and seen very faintly (with no clear front) in GOES CCOR-1. No source has been found for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, indicating its far-sidedness. There is a barely noticeable restructuring of the magnetic field far behind the southeast limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-05-12T09Z that seems to confirm the far-sided source.

note: Faint CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1, the front fades in the LASCO C2 field of view. The source may be some weak field line movement over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2025-05-12T17:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-12T23:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is two very large filament eruption, one seen on the Earth facing disk, and the other on the far side. The Earth facing filament has footpoints at approx. N20W50 and N50E60, where as the far sided filament appears to be just beyond the NW limb. These filaments are best seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with dimming and field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. In coronagraphs, the on disk eruption appears to over shadow the far sided eruption, and they appear as one feature.

note: Wide, relatively slow CME seen to the northeast in SOHO C2, C3, and GOES CCOR1 and to the north in STEREO Ahead COR2 clearly associated with a strong far-sided eruption as evidenced by a large-scale prominence eruption occurring off the northeast limb seen best in GOES SUVI 284 seen starting around 2025-05-13T14:05Z but clearly visible more broadly by 15:00Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames before overlapping CME: 2025-05-14T07:12Z overtakes this event. The source is likely far-sided and related to an opening of field lines observed over the northwest limb starting around 2025-05-14T06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171,193 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2. It is unclear if this CME is also visible in STEREO A COR2 due to data quality as well as GOES CCOR-1 due to obstruction from the control arm. The source appears to be an M2.1 flare from AR 14087 with associated filament ejecta best seen in SDO/AIA 304 and 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen in the NNE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-15T21:28Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. This event only visible in later frames of STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-05-25T19:53Z to 2025-05-18T01:53Z. The source of this event is a filament eruption from AR 4087 (N15W42) following an M2.1 class flare which resulted in associated CME: 2025-05-15T18:00Z. This eruption can be seen exhibiting a strong Northwestern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

The source of this event may be a very faint dimming/post-eruptive arcades at around (N25E50) prior to 2025-05-16T08:00Z, best seen in SDO AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen eastward in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR and STEREO A COR2, but not yet well-formed in C2 until it exits its field of view. Its source is uncertain but is likely one of the many instances of gradual opening of field lines seen on or beyond the SE limb in UV imagery. One such instance of subtle movement can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 171 around 2025-05-17T21:00Z, located at about S35 on or beyond the E limb.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. Not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1. No source for it was found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the west, only seen in a few early timestamps of STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2. Also visible in GOES CCOR-1. This CME seems to follow in the footsteps of 2025-05-18T12:36Z CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Large, bright CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-19T00:00Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a large filament eruption centered at approximately N50E10 with a gradual liftoff beginning at approximately 2025-05-18T19:00Z. This filament can be seen exhibiting some Northwestern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with dimming visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211, field line opening visible in SDO AIA 171 and post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 131 and 193.

The source is an on-disk filament eruption and brightening centered around S35E55 in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 beginning around 2025-05-20T19:39Z. Also observed well as field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193. Visible deflection of the ejecta southward is observed in the SDO AIA and GOES SUVI field of view. This is the second of two overlapping CMEs from this same source, following the faster CME 2025-05-20T20:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Very faint front seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2. This is one of several successive faint fronts associated with a gradual streamer blowout seen to the NE. Gradual opening field line movement can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 over the course of several hours during this blowout. The faint leading edge becomes diffuse before reaching edge of the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view. Obstructed by pylon in GOES CCOR-1. Not discernable in STEREO A COR2 due to faintness.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-24T18:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a C5.3 flare and subsequent eruption from AR 4098 (S05W40) seen exhibiting Western deflection in SDO AIA 193 and 211.

note: Narrow faint jet to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1, and (most likely) in STEREO A COR2, overlapping with/partly obscured by an earlier jet/outflow seen to the west. There is a possible very faint shock in C2 that is wider than the narrow denser bulk. The source of this CME is likely the M8.9 flare from Active Region 14098 (S05W50) peaking at 2025-05-25T16:30Z and the associated filament eruption seen as ejecta starting at 2025-05-25T16:43Z in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 193 and as dimming in EUVI A 195 and SDO AIA 193.

note: Faint narrow CME/outflow with unclear front overlapping with/obscured by outflows from the previous CME in this direction, faintly seen in SOHO, STEREO A COR2 and in CCOR-1. No source has been found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: A relatively bright CME seen to the east in all three coronagraphs. Its source is the M1.4 flare from AR 14100 (N12E70) and the associated ejecta seen in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI/EUVI A 304 around 2025-05-26T13:21Z (ejecta directed northward). Coronal signatures include intense dimming, brightening, post-eruptive arcades and even a wide EUV wave seen almost reaching the central meridian in SDO AIA.

note: Faint CME observed to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. This CME is best observed later in the C2 and C3 FOV as it develops, appearing only faintly around the occulting disk at the start time. This CME front is followed by numerous outflowing material. The source is not certain, and could be related to persistent field line movement for several hours over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171, starting as early as 2025-07-04T21:07Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Super faint CME with a front to S best seen in the running difference imagery in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1  and very faintly in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. No clear source found in EUV imagery, however there is very slowly developing dimming centered (S50E15) just E of the southern CH, as seen in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-07-06T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 14127 (S19W47) beginning at approx. 2025-07-06T00:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. This CME is likely deflected Northward by a Southern coronal hole, and is quickly overtaken by following CME: 2025-07-06T02:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet-like CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-07-06T15:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 14127 (S19W56) beginning at approx. 2025-07-06T14:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 193. This CME is likely deflected towards the North by a Southern oriented coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: A faint CME with a fuzzy front dissipating soon (or father a sequence of fuzzy faint fronts following each other almost immediately). The CME is directed to the west-northwest seen in SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs. Its initial front is too faint to be seen in C3, but it can faintly be seen as one of the follow-up fronts in C3. The source of this CME is a filament eruption happening behind the northwest limb as seen from STEREO A EUVI 195/304 - especially note the wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field on/behind the limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 starting at 2025-07-06T17:05Z, and a bit later a minor but bright post-eruptive peeking from behind the west limb in EUVI A 304. SDO AIA 304/171 and GOES SUVI 304 also possibly see this eruption - but as a loop-like filament that seems to slowly depart the limb around 17:18Z, after first starting to rise as a sizable loop some time as early as 15:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME observed to the far north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely sympathetic with an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22 that had an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z, also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. This front is not from the main ejecta of this eruption, but appears to be triggered alongside simultaneous fronts in other directions, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z (bright NE bulk) and CME 2025-07-08T04:36Z (NE, more in ecliptic).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the west in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to an opening of field lines on or beyond the western limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 imagery starting around 2025-07-09T10:55Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The CME start time is actually 2025-07-09T13:25Z (4 hours earlier than the start time in DONKI). This is because SOHO LASCO was not available on the day when the CME was analyzed and entered into DONKI. CME with a flux rope clearly seen in coronagraphs, first seen to the NW in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-07-09T17:30Z. CME is also seen to the N in STEREO A COR2. CME was originally covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, but LASCO eventually backfilled. A possible source for this CME is a filament eruption starting to the SW of AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-09T15:30Z and moving eastward - faint ejecta can be seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA 304. If this candidate is the source of the CME, there is some significant deflection to the NW.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint CME with two lobes seen to the north in SOHO LASCO and in GOES CCOR-1 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 and closely following the wider, slightly slower, preceding CME: 2025-07-09T17:30Z. This CME is partially obscured by the pylon in C3. Its source has not been found, but is likely the same Active Region 4137 that produced the preceding, 2025-07-09T17:30Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME to the NW seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and obscured by pylon in C3; not really seen in other coronagraphs. It is the second faint front (the earlier, 03Z front is even fainter and disappears really quickly in C2 imagery). Source is likely a slowly developing, messy eruption near AR 4037, centered ~(N32W23), starting as early as 2025-07-1tT00:54Z and lasting through the whole morning (at least to 5Z). The eruption location seems to move further west with time. Coronal signatures include developing faint dimming and faint post-eruptive arcades, as seen in SDO AIA 193/304, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CME with a narrower bulk and a wider, fainter possible shock front visible to the NNW in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the N in STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T18:36Z. CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and very faintly in STEREO A COR2. A possible source of this CME is a small eruption best seen near the SW limb in SDO AIA 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:03Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely some opening field lines from beyond the NW limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:16Z. CME likely combines with following, faster CME: 2025-07-13T22:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T22:12Z. CME is also seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is most likely an eruption from AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-13T21:44Z best seen in GOES SUVI 284. The eruption can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and STEREO A EUVI 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:35Z followed by an EUV wave. CME collides and likely combines with previous, slower CME: 2025-07-13T19:24Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint flux rope CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Exact source is uncertain, but is very likely associated with continued outflow to the NW from near AR 4137 (N19W81) or beyond the NW limb, following the eruptions associated with CME:2025-07-13T19:24Z and CME:2025-07-13T22:12Z which were both to the NW as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is an eruption from former Active Region 14134 (S22W118) at 2025-07-14T13:45Z seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. This eruption immediately triggers the eruption of a nearby filament which spans from about S45W72 to S20W102 with liftoff starting at about 2025-07-14T15:15Z as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines and ejecta can be seen on the SW limb, originating from AR 14134, and filamentary ejecta can be seen departing from the SW limb with heavy southward deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304/284 and SDO AIA 304/193/171/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1
